V{{Infobox philosopher\u000a| region           = [[French philosophy]]\u000a| era              = [[18th-century philosophy]]\u000a| image            = Yves-Marie André.jpg\u000a| image_size       = thumb\u000a| alt              = \u000a| caption          = \u000a| name             = Yves-Marie André\u000a| other_names      = le Père André\u000a| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1675|05|22}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living philosophers, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead -->\u000a| birth_place      = [[Châteaulin]], [[Finistère]]\u000a| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1764|02|26|1675|05|22}} <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\u000a| death_place      = [[Caen]], [[Calvados]]\u000a| school_tradition = \u000a| main_interests   = [[Aesthetics]]\u000a| notable_ideas    = \u000a| influences       = \u000a| influenced       = \u000a| signature        = \u000a| signature_alt    = \u000a| quote            =\u000a| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\u000a}}'''Yves Marie André ''' (1675\u20131764), also known as '''le Père André''',  was a French [[Jesuit]] [[mathematician]], [[philosopher]], and [[essayist]].\u000a\u000aAndré entered the Society of Jesus in 1693. Although distinguished in his scholastic studies, he adhered to [[Gallicanism]] and [[Jansenism]] and was thus considered unsuitable for responsible office by Church authorities. He therefore pursued scientific studies and became royal professor of mathematics at Caen.<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Yves Marie André}}</ref>\u000a\u000aHe is best known for his ''Essai sur le Beau'' (''Essay on Beauty''), a 1741 philosophical work on [[aesthetics]], which made him famous at the time and remained a well-known work into the 19th century.<ref>André, ''Essai sur le Beau'' in ''\u0152uvres Philosophiques'' (Paris: Adolphe Delahays, 1843).</ref>\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [https://archive.org/details/oeuvresphilosop01andrgoog